> If you use an anti-lock to counteract a lock held by the caller, then this invalidates the assumption that holding a lock across a function call protects the state guarded by the lock.
If the anti-lock requires access to the lock guard, then this canâ€™t happen unless the caller passes a reference to the guard, in which case itâ€™s aware that the callee might unlock the guard.
Rustâ€™s pretty popular â€˜parking_lotâ€™ crate has such an API on its guards called â€˜unlockedâ€™, which takes a closure and temporarily unlocks the mutex while the closure is running.





